Φ(Prescriptive_Analytics) = (Ω∘λ∘σ)(observation) ⊕ action_closure + ε

Where:
  σ :: observation → prediction       ("what will happen?")
  λ :: prediction  → decision         ("how do we benefit?")
  Ω :: (σ, λ)      → loop_closure     ("how will decisions impact everything else?")
  ε :: implicit valence — the "should" that enters once λ becomes prescription

Composition:
  descriptive  = σ alone over historical observation
  predictive   = σ alone over projected observation
  prescriptive = (Ω ∘ λ ∘ σ) — the third phase that subsumes the first two

Signature:
  loop_closure ≠ feedback.
  Feedback returns signal to σ for another pass while the model is held fixed.
  Closure places action inside the observation space — the decision alters
  what can be observed next. The model itself moves. This is the move from
  spectator to participant in the analytics frame.

Invariant:
  The prescriptive move is irreversible. Once you ask "what should we do?"
  you cannot return to "what will happen?" as if the question were innocent.
  The prediction space is now shaped by the action space; the action space
  carries valence the prediction space did not.

Consequence:
  ε is not a contaminant of the formal system but a load-bearing element.
  Pure forecasts can be ε-free. Prescriptions cannot. The "should" is the
  bridge by which subjective valence enters mathematical recommendation.

| :integrating
